const Q_CRK_2019_MODEL_II=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul taught that spiritual gifts in all their varieities emanate from  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the one body of Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man's cordial relationship with God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the one spirit of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men's ability to interpret</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament, specifically in 1 Corinthians 12:4-6, Paul taught that there are different kinds of spiritual gifts, but the same Spirit is the source of all of them. Therefore, the correct answer is 'the one spirit of God'.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE BENEFITS OF SPIRITUAL GIFTS TO THE INDIVIDUAL AND THE CHURCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God charged man to 'be fruitful, and multiply, and .... the earth, and subdue it'. (1st creation story)</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fill</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">renew </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">replenish</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stock</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Genesis 1:28, God commanded man to 'be fruitful, and multiply, and fill the earth, and subdue it'. Therefore, the correct answer is 'fill'.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One significant lesson from Jonah's response to the outcome of his message was that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God is slow to anger</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God will allow supernatural consequences direct the steps of men to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the providence and mercies of God are universal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the benevolence of God is not for the sinful</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The story of Jonah in the Bible teaches us about God's mercy and compassion, not just for the Israelites, but for all people. When Jonah finally obeyed God's command to go to Nineveh and warn its people of their wickedness, they repented, and God spared them. This shows that God's providence and mercies are universal, not limited to a particular group of people.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Woe is me! For I am lost\". This was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prophet Ezekiel's declaration when he saw the dry bones</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the declaration of Isaiah when he saw the glory of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made by Moses in the wilderness of Sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the statement of Jeremiah when he foretold the punishment of God to Israel</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase \"Woe is me! For I am lost\" is from the book of Isaiah 6:5. It was Isaiah's response when he saw the glory of God in a vision and realized his own sinfulness and unworthiness. None of the other options correctly identify the speaker or the context of this statement.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Matthew's account, John the Baptist's immediate reaction when Jesus came to be baptized was to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ask why he should baptize a non-sinner</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">baptize Him immediately</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wait for the promise of the manifestation of God's glory</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ask that Jesus should rather baptize him</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Matthew 3:14, when Jesus came to John the Baptist to be baptized, John tried to deter him, saying, 'I need to be baptized by you, and do you come to me?' This implies that John felt that Jesus, being the Messiah, was more worthy and should rather be the one baptizing him.</div>", "topic": "THE BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE MEANING AND PURPOSE OF THE BAPTISM OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the following is not a quality  of good discipleship</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total commitment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exuberance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prompt response</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">self-denial</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Exuberance, while it can be a positive trait, is not necessarily a quality of good discipleship. Good discipleship is characterized by qualities such as total commitment, prompt response, and self-denial, which involve putting the needs and commands of Jesus before one's own desires. Exuberance, or high energy and enthusiasm, is not inherently negative, but it is not a defining characteristic of discipleship.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Jesus healed the paralytic, the anger of the scribes was aroused by His</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">healing of the man on a Sabbath</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">claim to forgive sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">refusal to show them signs of His divinity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">nature of command to the paralytic</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Mark 2:1-12, when Jesus healed the paralytic man, He first told the man that his sins were forgiven. This statement was what aroused the anger of the scribes because they believed that only God could forgive sins, and they considered Jesus' claim as blasphemy. Therefore, the correct answer is 'claim to forgive sins'.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Hosanna to the son of David! Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord, Hosanna in the highest!\" This was... acoount of the Triumphal Entry</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Luke's</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Matthew's</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John's</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mark's</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'Hosanna to the son of David! Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord, Hosanna in the highest!' is found in the Gospel of Matthew, specifically in Matthew 21:9. This was when Jesus made his triumphal entry into Jerusalem, and the crowds were shouting these praises. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Matthew's'.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following was Pilate's question to Jesus at his trial?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Are you Jesus, the prophet from Galilee?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is it that these men testify against you?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Are you the king of the Jews?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What evil have you done?</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of John 18:33, Pilate asked Jesus 'Are you the king of the Jews?' during his trial. This question was asked to ascertain the claims made about Jesus being a king, which was seen as a threat to the Roman Empire.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE PILATE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Gospel according to St. Matthew, Jesus sent His disciples to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Gentiles</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Greeks</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Samaritans</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Jews</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Gospel according to St. Matthew, specifically in Matthew 10:5-6, Jesus instructed His disciples not to go among the Gentiles or enter any town of the Samaritans, but rather go to the lost sheep of Israel (the Jews). This was because Jesus' initial mission was to the Jews before it extended to the Gentiles.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COMMISSIONING AND MISSION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An ideal Christian family according to St. Paul is one in which all but one of the following prevail</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wives are subject to their husbands</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husbands love their wives</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fathers do not provoke their children</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">husbands treat their wives as heirs</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Ephesians 5:22-33, St. Paul advises wives to submit to their husbands and husbands to love their wives. In Colossians 3:21, he also advises fathers not to provoke their children. However, there is no specific verse where St. Paul advises husbands to treat their wives as heirs. Therefore, the correct answer is option 4.</div>", "topic": "INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS : RELATIONSHIP IN THE CHRISTIAN FAMILY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Jeremiah, the Lord's new covenant will be made with the house of ... and the house of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah, Elisha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Israel, Judah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Judah, Levi</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Israel, Jacob</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jeremiah 31:31-34, God promises to make a new covenant with the house of Israel and the house of Judah. This new covenant would not be like the one He made with their ancestors when He took them by the hand to lead them out of Egypt. This time, God promises to put His law in their minds and write it on their hearts. He will be their God, and they will be His people. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Josiah's reforms extended to the following areas except</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the practice of sacred prostitution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abolition of Assyrian astral cult</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cleansing of the temple of all foreign objects</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving recognition to the priests in high places</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Josiah's reforms were aimed at purifying the religious practices of the Israelites. He abolished the practice of sacred prostitution, removed the Assyrian astral cult, and cleansed the temple of all foreign objects. However, he did not give recognition to the priests in high places. This was not part of his reforms.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzer king of Babylon invaded Jerusalem and carried away all the treasures of the temple during the reign of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehoiachin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jehoiakim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mannaseh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mattaniah</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar, the king of Babylon, invaded Jerusalem and carried away all the treasures of the temple during the reign of Jehoiachin. Jehoiachin was a king of Judah who, according to the Hebrew Bible, was taken into captivity by Nebuchadnezzar after a reign of only three months and ten days.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : THE FALL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Ezekiel was called, he was shown a scroll on which were written words of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamentations, bitterness and woe</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wisdom, understanding and right judgement</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lamentations, mourning and woe</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bitterness, right judgement and mourning</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Ezekiel, specifically Ezekiel 2:10, it is mentioned that when Ezekiel was called, he was shown a scroll on which were written words of 'lamentations, mourning and woe'. However, the term 'mourning' is replaced with 'bitterness' in some translations. Therefore, the correct answer is 'lamentations, bitterness and woe'.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF EZEKIEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the parable of the Sower, the seeds that fell upon thorns, signify those who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive the word but the cares and delight in riches of the world choke them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive the word but the evil one comes and snatches it away</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive the word with joy, but it has no root in them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive the word, it endures for a while, but falls away with tribulation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the parable of the Sower, as told in Matthew 13:22, the seeds that fell among thorns represent those who hear the word, but the worries of this life and the deceitfulness of wealth choke the word, making it unfruitful. Therefore, the correct answer is 'receive the word but the cares and delight in riches of the world choke them'.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the following is common to the missions of the twelve and the seventy? Both were </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sent in pairs with authority to heal the sick</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sent only to the lost sheep of the house of Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to carry no purse, no bag, no sandals and to salute no one on the road</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sent to preach the kingdom of God and heal the sick</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The missions of the twelve and the seventy were both to preach the kingdom of God and heal the sick. This is evident in the Bible, specifically in Luke 9:1-2 for the twelve and Luke 10:1-9 for the seventy. The other options are either specific to one group or not mentioned in the Bible.</div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE TWELVE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Do not be afraid; for I know what you seek, Jesus who was crucified...\" This statement was made</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by Joseph of Arimathea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to Mary Salome, Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">by Peter, James and John</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'Do not be afraid; for I know that you seek Jesus who was crucified...' was made to Mary Magdalene and the other Mary (mother of James) by an angel at the tomb of Jesus. This is recorded in Matthew 28:5-6. The other options are incorrect as they do not align with the biblical account.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Non-tolerance of the Church for hypocrisy and greed was pointed out particularly in the story of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Naboth's vineyard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ananias and Sapphira</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gehazi's greed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elymas, the magician at Paphos</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The story of Ananias and Sapphira in the book of Acts (Acts 5:1-11) clearly demonstrates the Church's non-tolerance for hypocrisy and greed. Ananias and Sapphira sold a piece of property and lied about the amount of money they received from the sale, keeping back some of the money for themselves. When confronted by Peter, they both lied and were struck dead as a result.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter refuted the mockery of drunkiness of the disciples by refering to the prophecy of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiel</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">On the day of Pentecost, when the Holy Spirit descended on the disciples, they began to speak in other tongues. Some people in the crowd mocked them, saying they were drunk. Peter stood up and addressed the crowd, saying that the disciples were not drunk, but were experiencing the fulfillment of the prophecy of Joel (Joel 2:28-32), where God promised to pour out His Spirit on all people.</div>", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH : THE PENTECOST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According ot the Sermon on the Mount, those who hunger and thirst for righteousness shall </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inherit God's kingdom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inherit the Earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be satisfied</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be comforted</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Sermon on the Mount, specifically Matthew 5:6, Jesus said 'Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'be satisfied'.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE DEMANDS OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"I am the resurrection and the life, he who believes in me, though he dies, yet shall he live\". Jesus directed this statement to   </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lazarus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Martha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mary</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically John 11:25-26, Jesus directed the statement 'I am the resurrection and the life, he who believes in me, though he dies, yet shall he live' to Martha, the sister of Lazarus. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Martha'.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE RESURRECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When John baptized Jesus, at river Jordan, he described him as the Lamb of God who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had existed before him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they have been expecting</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was bearing the mark of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">takes away the sin of the world</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically John 1:29, John the Baptist refers to Jesus as the 'Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world'. This is a reference to the sacrificial system of the Old Testament where a lamb without blemish was sacrificed for the sins of the people. Jesus, as the Lamb of God, is seen as the ultimate sacrifice for the sins of all humanity.</div>", "topic": "THE BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE MEANING AND PURPOSE OF THE BAPTISM OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of John, Jesus referred to himself as the 'true vine' which means that Jesus</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is the true source of happiness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">and the believer are a tree and its branches </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was a vine dresser</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was referring to the bread and wine for last supper</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 15:1, Jesus refers to himself as the 'true vine' and his followers as the branches. In this metaphor, Jesus is teaching that just as the branches draw their life from the vine, so must his followers remain in him to have life. This means that believers are dependent on Jesus for spiritual life and fruitfulness.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE TRUE VINE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The two sons of Samuel who took bribe and perverted justice were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joel and Abijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hophni and Phinehas</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joel and Abinadab</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Phinehas and Ramah</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically 1 Samuel 8:1-3, it is mentioned that Samuel's two sons, Joel and Abijah, did not follow his ways. Instead, they turned aside after dishonest gain, took bribes, and perverted justice. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Joel and Abijah'.</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Since fervent prayers of the righteous has great power in its effects, Christians according to St. James must</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be steadfast in prayer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">confess and forsake their sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have faith while praying</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not ask wrongly</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James 5:16, it is written that 'The prayer of a righteous person is powerful and effective.' Therefore, Christians are encouraged to be steadfast in prayer. While the other options also have biblical basis, the question specifically refers to the power of prayer, making 'be steadfast in prayer' the most directly relevant answer.</div>", "topic": "EFFECTIVE PRAYER : THE REQUIREMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To St. James, a doer of the word of God must learn to also</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">control his tongue</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">combine his faith with work</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persevere in times of tribulation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be a listener of the word of God</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James, the author emphasizes the importance of controlling one's tongue as a part of being a doer of the word of God. James 1:26 says, 'If anyone thinks he is religious and does not bridle his tongue but deceives his heart, this person's religion is worthless.' This means that controlling the tongue is a significant part of demonstrating one's faith in action.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : THE BENEFITS OF BEING JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"What you sow does not come to life unless it dies\". This was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the message of St. Paul's teaching on the second coming of Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the response St. Paul instructed Christians to give to those who doubt the resurrection of Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the statement of Jesus to Martha</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made by St. Paul to Elymas, the magician</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'What you sow does not come to life unless it dies' is from 1 Corinthians 15:36, and it was used by St. Paul to explain the concept of resurrection to those who doubted it. He used the analogy of a seed dying in the ground and then sprouting into new life to illustrate how the resurrection works. Therefore, this phrase was a part of St. Paul's response to those who doubted the resurrection of Christ.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The mystery of lawlessness, deception and wickedness will commence as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the signs of the second coming of the Lord</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the aftermath of the second coming of the Lord</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a demonstration of the destruction of the world</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a consequence of man's evil deeds</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The mystery of lawlessness, deception and wickedness will commence as the signs of the second coming of the Lord. This is based on the biblical teachings that these signs will precede the second coming of Jesus Christ. The other options are not correct because they do not align with the biblical teachings on the subject.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : THE SIGNS OF THE COMING OF CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul supported his admonition on 'Dignity of Labour' by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">instructing Christians not to tolerate laziness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encouraging hardwork and good living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving an example of himself</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">charging Christians to support the Church</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul supported his admonition on 'Dignity of Labour' by giving an example of himself. In the New Testament, Paul often used his own life as an example to illustrate his teachings. He worked as a tentmaker to support himself while he was preaching, demonstrating the value of hard work and self-sufficiency. The other options, while they may be true in other contexts, are not the specific ways that Paul supported his admonition on the 'Dignity of Labour'.</div>", "topic": "DIGNITY OF LABOUR : BENEFITS OF DIGNITY OF LABOUR"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul on 'Civic Responsibility' advised Christians not only to be law-abiding but also</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to provide moral advice to those in authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resist any illegitimate government</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">do what is expected of them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shun membership of unlawful societies</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul in his teachings emphasized that Christians should not only obey the law but also fulfill their civic responsibilities. This means doing what is expected of them in their society, which includes but is not limited to paying taxes, voting, and participating in community service. This aligns with the third option 'do what is expected of them'.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE REQUIREMENTS OF GOOD CITIZENSHIP."}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The illustration of Satan, the adversary who prowls around seeking whom to devour, is particular to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on humility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on the second coming of Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Peter's teaching on humility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Peter's teaching on civic responsibility</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The illustration of Satan as an adversary prowling around seeking whom to devour is found in 1 Peter 5:8, which is part of St. Peter's teachings. Therefore, the correct answer is 'St. Peter's teaching on humility'. This teaching is about being vigilant and sober-minded because of the adversary, Satan. It is not directly related to civic responsibility or the second coming of Christ.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'If one is in Christ, then he is ...' - St. Paul's teaching on Christians as Sons and Heirs of God.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in new life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">redeemed from sin and death</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abraham's offspring according to the promise</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">part of God's Chosen generation</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Galatians 3:29, St. Paul states, 'If you belong to Christ, then you are Abraham's seed, and heirs according to the promise.' This means that those who are in Christ are considered Abraham's offspring according to the promise.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : HOW CHRISTIANS ARE JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">... according to St. Paul should not be the reason for continuing sinful lives</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">baptism by immersion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the grace of God </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the resurrection of Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the justification of Christians by faith</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 6:1-2, St. Paul states, 'What shall we say, then? Shall we go on sinning so that grace may increase? By no means! We are those who have died to sin; how can we live in it any longer?' This implies that the grace of God should not be a reason for continuing sinful lives.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The essence of St. Paul's teaching on Law and Grace is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's grace in Christians' lives shouldn't be a reason for continuing in sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">observance of the law is necesary for redemption in Christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">observance of the law only isn't a guarantee of salvation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">what God truly rewards is the prayer for grace by Christians</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on Law and Grace emphasizes that God's grace is not a license for Christians to continue in sin. He taught that while the law reveals sin, grace provides salvation through faith in Jesus Christ. Therefore, the grace of God in the lives of Christians should lead to righteousness, not a continuation in sin.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"The gods have come down to us in the likeness of men!\" this was statement was made by the people of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lystra</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cyprus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Iconium</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joppa</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"The gods have come down to us in the likeness of men!\" was made by the people of Lystra. This happened in the book of Acts 14:8-18 when Paul healed a man who was lame from birth. The people of Lystra, seeing the miracle, thought Paul and Barnabas were gods (Zeus and Hermes) who had come down in human form.</div>", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH : THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herod Agrippa persecuted Peter primarily to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">please the Jews</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obstruct the spread of the gospel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">contain the news about Jesus' resurrection</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">signal to the Apostles that he wouldn't tolerate them</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herod Agrippa persecuted Peter primarily to please the Jews. This is evident in Acts 12:1-3 where it is stated that Herod arrested some who belonged to the church, intending to persecute them. He had James, the brother of John, put to death with the sword. When he saw that this met with approval among the Jews, he proceeded to seize Peter also.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philip converted the Ethiopian Eunuch on a pilgrimage to ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jerusalem</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lystra</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joppa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macedonia</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philip converted the Ethiopian Eunuch on a pilgrimage to Jerusalem. This is recorded in Acts 8:26-40. The Ethiopian Eunuch was a high official in charge of all the treasury of Candace, queen of the Ethiopians. He had gone to Jerusalem to worship and was returning home; sitting in his chariot he was reading the prophet Isaiah. Then the Spirit told Philip, 'Go to that chariot and stay near it.' Philip ran up to the chariot and heard the man reading Isaiah the prophet. He asked, 'Do you understand what you are reading?' 'How can I,' he said, 'unless someone explains it to me?' So he invited Philip to come up and sit with him. Philip began with that very passage of Scripture and told him the good news about Jesus.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : CONVERSION OF THE ETHIOPIAN EUNUCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's love for man is considered to have started from the...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">act of sending Jesus to die for the redemption of mankind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">creation of the world</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">covenant with Abraham and his descendants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">new commandment of Christ</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's love for man is considered to have started from the creation of the world. This is because God created man in His own image and likeness, and gave him dominion over all other creatures (Genesis 1:26-28). This act of creation signifies God's love for man. The act of sending Jesus for redemption, the covenant with Abraham, and the new commandment of Christ are all subsequent manifestations of God's love, but they did not mark the beginning of His love for man.</div>", "topic": "LOVE : GOD'S LOVE FOR MAN"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the synoptic of John, the statement \"this is indeed the prophet who is to come into the world\" was made by the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disciples of Jesus when He walked on the sea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people who witnessed the turning of water into wine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people present at the feeding of the Five Thousand</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pharisees during the baptism of Jesus</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of John, the statement \"this is indeed the prophet who is to come into the world\" was made by the people present at the feeding of the Five Thousand (John 6:14). After Jesus fed the five thousand with five loaves of bread and two fish, the people recognized Him as the prophet that was to come into the world, as prophesied in the Old Testament (Deuteronomy 18:15). The other options are incorrect because they do not align with the biblical account.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF: THE BREAD OF LIFE AND THE LIVING WATER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus left for the other side of the sea when the multitude that came to Him had been fed beause</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He needed to pray</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people sought after Him for feeding and miracles</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He needed time for Himself alone</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people wanted to test Him</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically John 6:15, it is mentioned that after Jesus fed the multitude, they wanted to make Him king. To avoid this, Jesus withdrew to the mountain by Himself. Therefore, the closest correct answer is that the people sought after Him for feeding and miracles.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF: THE BREAD OF LIFE AND THE LIVING WATER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At about the ... hour, Jesus cried with a loud voice \"Eli Eli lama sabach - thani\".</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eleventh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ninth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">seventh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sixth</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically Matthew 27:46 and Mark 15:34, it is mentioned that at the ninth hour, Jesus cried out \"Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani?\" which means \"My God, My God, why have You forsaken Me?\". Therefore, the correct answer is the ninth hour.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Only ...stated that the transfiguration took place eight days after Peter's confession of Jesus as the son of God.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Luke</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Matthew</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mark</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, it is only in the book of Luke (Luke 9:28) that it is specifically stated that the transfiguration of Jesus took place about eight days after Peter's confession of Jesus as the son of God. The other gospels (Matthew, Mark, and John) do not specify the number of days.</div>", "topic": "THE TRANSFIGURATION : THE EVENTS LEADING TO THE TRANSFIGURATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One significant lesson surrounding the birth of Jesus is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is need for us to have faith in the word of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the humble nature of one's birth does not affect one's greatness in life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sacrifice of purification is important at the one's birth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">one's humble birth is as important a criteria for greatness as it is of salvation</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The birth of Jesus, which took place in a humble setting (a manger), signifies that the humble nature of one's birth does not affect one's greatness in life. Jesus, despite his humble birth, went on to become the savior of the world. This teaches us that greatness is not determined by the circumstances of one's birth but by one's actions and impact in life.</div>", "topic": "THE BIRTH AND EARLY LIFE OF JESUS : THE BIRTH AND BOYHOOD OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God proclaimed through Jeremiah that He would destroy the land with ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">drought, famine and pestilence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sword, famine and pestilence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">firestorm, drought and famine</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">earthquake, famine and pestilence</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is found in Jeremiah 14:12, where God says He will destroy the land with sword, famine and pestilence.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : THE FALL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"But the house of Israel will not listen to you...\" the addressee here is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The quote is from Ezekiel 3:7, which indicates that the addressee is Ezekiel.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF EZEKIEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"For I desire steadfast love and not sacrifice...\" this statement relates to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">message of God's love to man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">response of Israel to the genuiness of God's love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">response of God's love to the children of Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">message of Hosea on faithfulness and social progress</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"For I desire steadfast love and not sacrifice...\" is a part of the message of the prophet Hosea. Hosea emphasized the importance of faithfulness and love over ritualistic sacrifices. He preached that God values genuine love and faithfulness more than ritualistic sacrifices, which were often performed without true devotion. This is a message of faithfulness and social progress, as it encourages people to be faithful and loving, which leads to a better society.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">... was opposed Amos during the preaching of his message on social justice and true religion</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Uziah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amaziah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The king of Bethel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The king of Judah</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amaziah, the priest of Bethel, opposed Amos during his preaching of his message on social justice and true religion. Amaziah accused Amos of conspiracy and told him to go back to Judah. He did not want Amos to prophesy in Bethel because it was the king's sanctuary and a temple of the kingdom. Therefore, the correct answer is Amaziah.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">... updated Nehemiah about the state of Jerusalem while he was ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezra, a captive in Babylon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zerubbabel, an Emperor in Babylon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiah, an Emperor in Babylon</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hanai, a captive in Babylon</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Nehemiah, it was Hanani (Nehemiah's brother) who updated Nehemiah about the state of Jerusalem while he was a captive in Babylon. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Hanai, a captive in Babylon'.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. James advised Christians against partiality particularly because they </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bear the faith of Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are the chosen generation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are at the risk of criticism by unbelievers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bear the seed of righteousness</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James (James 2:1), St. James advised Christians against showing favoritism because they bear the faith of our Lord Jesus Christ. Therefore, the correct answer is 'bear the faith of Jesus'.</div>", "topic": "IMPARTIALITY : CONCEPT OF IMPARTIALITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>51", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Eyptians encamped at ... when they pursued the Israelites</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Raphidim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pi-ha-hi-roth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the wilderness of Sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the sea </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Egyptians encamped at Pi-ha-hi-roth when they pursued the Israelites. This is recorded in Exodus 14:9, where it is stated that the Egyptians pursued the Israelites and overtook them encamped by the sea, beside Pi-ha-hi-roth, before Baal-Zephon.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>52", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Last Supper refers the last meal Jesus had with His disciples immediately before His...  </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">arrest and death</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crucification and death</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">betrayal and arrest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">arrest and crucification</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Last Supper refers to the last meal Jesus had with His disciples immediately before His arrest and death. This event is recorded in the Gospels (Matthew 26:17–30, Mark 14:12–26, Luke 22:7–39 and John 13:1–17:26). After the meal, Jesus was betrayed by Judas, one of his disciples, arrested and subsequently crucified.</div>", "topic": "THE LAST SUPPER : THE STORY OF THE LAST SUPPER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>53", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Who do men say that the Son of man is?\" Jesus asked this question</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to show that popular opinion matters the most in His recognition as Messiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in the context of the Great Confession</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at the scene of His Transfiguration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">to indicate that the Jews and Pharisees need to reckon with His Messiahship</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The question \"Who do men say that the Son of man is?\" was asked by Jesus in the context of the Great Confession. This is recorded in Matthew 16:13-20. Jesus asked His disciples this question to reveal their understanding of His identity. The Great Confession is the moment when Peter confesses that Jesus is the Christ, the Son of the living God.</div>", "topic": "THE GREAT CONFESSION : THE OCCASION OF THE GREAT CONFESSION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>54", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sparing of Saul's life demonstrated David's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interest in God's punishment of Saul</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">level of faith in God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genuine love for Saul so that God prefers him as King over Israel than Saul</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mission to appoint Abner as his army commander when he becomes King</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David's sparing of Saul's life demonstrated his level of faith in God. This is seen in 1 Samuel 24 and 26 where David had the opportunity to kill Saul but chose not to. David believed that it was not his place to harm the Lord's anointed, showing his faith and trust in God's plan and timing.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>55", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph's leadership quality was so exceptional so much that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pharaoh had to appoint him as Emperor</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Chief butler recommended him to Pharaoh</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">other nations of the world benefited from it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God rewarded his action of commiting adultery with Potiphar's wife</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joseph's leadership quality was indeed exceptional, but it was not to the extent that Pharaoh appointed him as Emperor. Rather, it was the Chief Butler who recommended him to Pharaoh after Joseph correctly interpreted his dream while they were both in prison. This recommendation led to Joseph's appointment as the governor of Egypt, not the Emperor. The other options are incorrect because Joseph's leadership did not directly benefit other nations, and God did not reward him for committing adultery with Potiphar's wife, an act he did not commit.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSEPH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model II>56", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most significant lesson at the scene of the Israelites' blame of Moses in their struggle and escape from Egypt is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God hardened the heart of Pharaoh to pursue the Israelites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moses' height of anger and intolerance was revealed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moses' courage and confidence in God saved the entire situation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they would have perfered to stay back and die in Egypt</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most significant lesson at the scene of the Israelites' blame of Moses in their struggle and escape from Egypt is that Moses' courage and confidence in God saved the entire situation. Despite the Israelites' complaints and blame, Moses remained steadfast and relied on God's guidance to lead the Israelites out of Egypt. The other options are incorrect because they do not accurately represent the main lesson from this event.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : EXAMPLES OF ABRAHAM, HEBREW MIDWIVES AND DAVID"}];
